==Old English==

===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*magaþi-'' (a feminine-suffixed form of the root represented by Old English [[mæg|mǣġ]] ‘kinsman, kinswoman’).  Cognate with Old Saxon [[magað]] (Dutch [[maagd]]), Old High German [[magad]] (German [[Magd]]), Gothic [[𐌼𐌰𐌲𐌰𐌸𐍃]].

====Spellings====
mægþ, mægeþ

====Pronunciation====
[[IPA]]: /mæjθ/

====Noun====
'''mæġþ''' ''f'' (''pl'' '''mæġþ''' or '''mæġþe''')
# a [[maiden]] or [[girl]]; a [[virgin]]

====Derived terms====
*[[mægþblæd|mæġþblæd]]
*[[mægþhad|mǣġþhād]]


